definition.value: A defense which is not a defense in and of itself, but instead includes a combination of other defenses: self-defense, provocation, insanity, and diminished responsibility.

A version of the abuse defense in which an individual experiencing the daily life of racial segregation and violence common in many inner cities in the United States causes a subjective state equivalent to that caused by survival in a violent battleground of war. As such it leads to a condition similar to a syndrome already recognized in both psychological and psychiatric practices, that is, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).
Artificial introduction of semen or spermatozoa into the vagina to facilitate fertilization.
An assisted reproductive technique that includes the direct handling and manipulation of oocytes and sperm to achieve fertilization in vitro.
In vitro fertilization technique that uses mitochondrial DNA from a healthy donor in order to prevent the transmission of mitochondrial disease.

The replacement of mitochondria in one or more cells to prevent or ameliorate disease. MRT originated as a special form of in vitro fertilisation in which some or all of the future baby's mitochondrial DNA comes from a third party. This technique is used in cases when mothers carry genes for mitochondrial diseases. The therapy is approved for use in the United Kingdom. A second application is to use autologous mitochondria to replace mitochondria in damaged tissue to restore the tissue to a functional state. This has been used in clinical research in the United States to treat cardiac-compromised newborns.

label.value: in vitro fertilization with intracytoplasmic sperm injection and donor egg

definition.value: An assisted fertilization technique consisting of the microinjection of a single viable sperm into an extracted ovum. It is used principally to overcome low sperm count, low sperm motility, inability of sperm to penetrate the egg, or other conditions related to infertility in persons with sperm.
A donation of some biological substance in order to satisfy some medical need.
The medical donation of gametes.
Transfer of preovulatory oocytes from donor to a suitable host. Oocytes are collected, fertilized in vitro, and transferred to a host that can be human or animal.
The donation of a person's sperm, typically for usage in assisted reproductive techniques.

The process by which a cell or cells are kept alive outside of the organism from which it was derived (i.e., kept from decay by means of a chemical agent, cooling, or a fluid substitute that mimics the natural state within the organism).
Procedures for collecting specimens.

The process of obtaining semen from male humans or other animals with the use of various methods, for the purposes of artificial insemination, or medical study (usually in fertility clinics). Semen can be collected via masturbation (e. g., from stallions and canids), prostate massage, artificial vagina, penile vibratory stimulation (vibroejaculation) and electroejaculation.
A penile condom used for the purposes of sperm collection. Collection condoms are made from silicone or polyurethane, as latex is somewhat harmful to sperm.
Usage of any of various surgical techniques to collect semen.

The surgical procedure of removing a small portion of tissue from the testicle and extracting any viable sperm cells from that tissue for use in further procedures, most commonly intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI) as part of in vitro fertilisation (IVF).

A procedure in which spermatozoa are extracted from a person after they have been pronounced legally brain dead. There has been significant debate over the ethicality and legality of the procedure, and on the legal rights of the child and surviving parent if the gametes are used for impregnation.
A means of inducing ejaculation through vibration.

A procedure used to obtain semen samples from sexually mature mammals. The procedure is used for breeding programs and research purposes in various species, as well as in the treatment of an ejaculatory dysfunction in humans.
Sexual stimulation through the usage of vibration, usually with a vibrator.
Stimulation of the penis using vibration.
Stimulation of the clitoris using vibration.

The transfer of mammalian embryos from an in vivo or in vitro environment to a suitable host to improve pregnancy or gestational outcome in human or animal. In human fertility treatment programs, preimplantation embryos ranging from the 4-cell stage to the blastocyst stage are transferred to the uterine cavity between 3-5 days after fertilization in vitro.

Introduction of object and/or substance into or onto body, including injection, implantation, infusion, perfusion, transfusion, irrigation, instillation, insertion, placement, replacement, packing, intubation, catheterization, and cannulation.
The act of fixing something firmly or setting something securely or deeply into the body.
To move body tissue or cells from donor site to recipient site.
Transference of a tissue or organ within an individual, between individuals of the same species, or between individuals of different species.
Application of a ligature to tie a vessel or strangulate a part.
A method of sterilization where the fallopian tubes are surgically ligated to prevent conception.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the fallopian tubes.
Sterilization by ligation of the fallopian tubes via tubal ligation.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the vas deferens.
Surgical removal of any part of the vas deferens.
Surgical removal of part or all of the vas deferens.
Surgical removal of the ductus deferens, or a portion of it. It is done in association with prostatectomy, or to induce infertility.
Any of various surgeries which aim to alter vocal pitch.
Any of various surgeries which aim to lower vocal pitch.
Any of various surgeries which aim to raise vocal pitch.
Any of various surgeries performed on the vocal folds, also known as the vocal cords.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the cervix of the uterus.
Surgical removal of the cervix.
The surgical removal of the uterine cervix.
Surgical removal of the uterine cervix and pelvic lymph nodes.
Trachelectomy in which the parametria and vaginal cuff are also excised.
Trachelectomy in which only the main body of the cervix is removed.
Surgical removal of a leiomyoma of the uterus.
Surgical removal of part of the uterine body, frequently performed as a treatment for leiomyomas.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the vaginal introitus.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the hymen.
Surgical repair of the hymen.
The surgical removal of all or part of the hymen.
A surgical procedure to remove the hymen.
Any surgical procedure that results in the construction or reconstruction of the hymen.
The temporary surgical restoration of the hymen.

Such procedures are not generally regarded as part of mainstream gynecology, but are available from some plastic surgery centers, particularly in the United States, Middle East, South Korea and Western Europe, generally as outpatient surgery. The normal aim is to cause bleeding during post-nuptial intercourse, which in some cultures is considered proof of virginity.
